title: For Sale:  Savage Model 6DL-N  Deluxe .22 Semi auto rifle
postcontent:
This model 6 DL-N is from pre-1968 (no serial #)  It's a 15 rd semi suto marked "22 H.S. SHORT, LONG or LONG RIFLE" SAVAGE ARMS Westfield Mass, USA.  Comes with leather sling with quick detach swivels.    I found magazine ads with it pictured from 1965 and 66.  They sold this model then for $93 then!  At that time, most centerfire rifles were under $180.  The Savage 110 centerfire rifles were sold for $110 then.   It has a deluxe monte carlo stock with nice comb and palm swell fro right handed shooter.  Rosewood endcap.  Some small marks on the stock and metal from handling over the past 45+ yrs.  Has flip down rear sight, rimfire 3/8 grooved top.  No rust or pitting, a few minor wear marks.  This rifle is one of those "click clack" Savage/Stevens rifles.  It's a slow soft semi auto action.  If you hold the trigger when you shoot (proper marksmenship follow thru), the action stays open, release the trigger, it closes and you shoot again.  It works the same as others if you just pull and release trigger also.

I don't need to sell this, but offering for $200 or trade.  It's not a $100 rifle.  there weren't many made like this and I'm seeing them sell for well over $200.  I'm thinking they made these for the older crowd when they came out with this model.  

trades:  ?  throw them at me!  You never know.  I may go to the niles show this saturday and carry with me, but if a deal pops before then...great.

title: For Sale:   PTR-91 15 20-Rd Mags and 800 Rds NATO FN 7.62x51 ammo
location: North Fayetteville/Raleigh/Durham, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Offering is a PTR model 91. This rifle was born when our Fed gov’t decided in Regulation ATF 922R that any new firearm could not have more than 10 imported parts in it. At the time the Heckler and Koch model 91 chambered in 7.62 NATO was one of the most popular rifles around and for good reason…

They run like tanks and are very accurate!

This is the civilian version of the German G3 design that has been used by their military since the 1950’s. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heckler_%26_Koch_G3

After the ban on imports, JLD industries bought the engineering and machining from HK to manufacture the model 91 here in the states. These rifles have had several evolutions since the original offering and are rock solid performers. here is the current model listing:

http://www.ptr91.com/rifles

Here are the specs for this particular variation:

18” Button-rifled heavy target barrel in 1 in 12 right hand twist
Semi-auto recoil operated
20 rd box magazine fed
Rotary diopter rear sight with bullet drop compensation set for 100,200,300 and 400 yards
The rifle comes with 15 Magazines, a Brugger and Thomet Picatinny rail mount for optics mount (150 bucks on its own), hard case, sight tool and manual

Bolt and trigger group are manufactured by HK, all other parts are JLD

The trigger is pretty darned good for a rifle of this type

Rifle has about 1000 rounds put down the pipe in its lifetime

To feed this rifle I have for sale 4x200 rds of NATO 7.62 ammo manufactured by Fabrique National of Belgium. Headstamp is 1977 manufacture. The only Military Surplus ammo more accurate and reliable than this is the Lithuanian variety and you can’t find either of them anywhere. If anyone offers them for sale, they are snapped up in seconds. These are berdan primed cases, so they require a berdan decapping die to reload them.

A flak jacket or flak vest is a form of body armor designed to provide protection from case fragments ("frag") from high explosive weaponry, such as anti-aircraft artillery ("flak"), grenades, some round shot used in shotguns and land mines and other lower-velocity projectiles. title: For Sale:  1944 Walther G43 semiautomatic sniper rifle, nearly all matching!
postcontent:
Up for sale is a ultra-rare G43 semiautomatic sniper rifle used by the Germans in World War 2.  This particular example is a Walther "ac" built in 1944.  I appears that the stock and upper handguard are not original - but they are very nice reproductions and include clearly defined Waffenamts.

The gas cylinder (electropencil), receiver (stamped), bolt (electropencil), fire pin housing (stamped), and bolt carrier (stamped) are numbers-matching.  The barrel is hallmarked "bys" so it is not apparently matching.

While the original gas piston is included with the purchase of the rifle, I replaced it with one made by Apfeltor Waffenfabrik - you can look up this great company on the web.  This gas cylinder allows you to change inserts and regulate the blowback gases and prevent potential damage to the receiver.  I have a couple different sized-aperture inserts included.

All other parts on the rifle are believed to be original including the magazine.  This weapon does not have a sling or cleaning rod.

The price for this piece of history is $2200.  I prefer to do face-to-face purchases only.
